2 Possible solutions¶

Solution #1¶

One can set simply a threshold basd on the maximum value of the resistance at clear sky moments (R_ck). That would look like this:

In [20]:
# naming f1
df["f1"] = np.where(df.R > R_ck.max(), 1, 0)

Solution #2¶

In order to detect where it started, one can calculate a mean rolling window. It is important to consider that the rolling window variables can be fine tunning as well. The basic solution could be as follows:

In [50]:
# Calculate Parzen window on the difference R 
df["dif_R"] = df.R.diff(periods=2)
# This function creates a smooth version of the difference PR_corr
df["parzen"] = df.dif_R.rolling(3, min_periods=1, win_type="parzen").sum()
# Detecting faults, fault is detected if it is more than 20% of the highes deviation
df["f2"] = np.where((abs(df.parzen) > (df.parzen.max() * 0.4)), 1, 0)
df.head()

Solution #3¶

Scipy library has as well some possible solutions and easy to implement. This library contains some interesting ML functions. In this case _findpeaks function can be implemented as follows:

In [52]:
# Based on the difference calculated from R 
# we create a new column with absolute values to detect peaks
df["R_abs_dif"] = df.dif_R.abs()
df.R_abs_dif.plot()
Out[52]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x140b07250c8>
In [75]:
# Peak detection
from scipy.signal import find_peaks
peaks, properties = find_peaks(df.R_abs_dif, prominence=(df.R_abs_dif.max() * 0.4), width=1)
peaks_list = peaks.tolist()
# creating a new column with peaks detected
df["f3"] = df.R_abs_dif * 0
df.loc[df.index[peaks_list], "f3"] = 1
df.head()

Thoughts¶

There are many functions that can detect a change in the timeseries data. It is important to find tune the functions to be used.

Additional info¶

An extra feature can be extracted from the timeseries data: Power loss, this could be also useful in case one want to detect power losses due to system resistances. It can be calculated as follows:

In [77]:
Impp = 30.85
Vmpp = 7.94
df["P_loss"] = ((Impp * Impp) * df.R) / (Impp * Vmpp)
fig, axes = plt.subplots(dpi=300)
df.P_loss.plot()
Out[77]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x140b9722848>

Peak detection algorithms can be implemented to detect high power losses.
